04:03:09.860 --> 04:03:14.180
 Jail cried out with pain as he stumbled on almost falling.

04:03:14.180 --> 04:03:19.620
 He regained his balance and backed away from Makin, limping as blood ran down the back of his leg.

04:03:20.580 --> 04:03:24.500
 Makin strode at him for the first time seeing fear in Jail's eyes.

04:03:24.500 --> 04:03:26.900
 "Do you remember?"

04:03:26.900 --> 04:03:32.580
 "In the tomb, beneath Haldis," Makin said, not breaking the stride.

04:03:32.580 --> 04:03:36.180
 "It was a fair fight," Jail said, pleading, shuffling away,

04:03:36.180 --> 04:03:37.940
 leaving a trail of blood from his wounded leg.

04:03:37.940 --> 04:03:44.820
 "He was your kin, and you betrayed him, you murdered him," Makin said.

04:03:44.820 --> 04:03:50.020
 Exploding into movement, leaping forwards, dancing to the side around Jail's sword,

04:03:50.020 --> 04:03:53.620
 a slice at Jail's arm, a yell, and the sword was falling.

04:03:53.620 --> 04:03:58.580
 They crashed into each other, limbs tangled, fell to the ground, rolled,

04:03:58.580 --> 04:04:02.260
 Jail finding new strength as he punched kicked and bit at Makin.

04:04:02.260 --> 04:04:07.300
 Makin grabbed one of Jail's arms, pinned it as they rolled together,

04:04:07.300 --> 04:04:10.100
 inched his knife blade up towards Jail's throats.

04:04:10.100 --> 04:04:12.580
 Jail's efforts redoubled.

04:04:12.580 --> 04:04:18.020
 His free fist, punching at Makin's head, his guts, anywhere, everywhere.

04:04:18.900 --> 04:04:20.980
 Makin grunted but did not let go.

04:04:20.980 --> 04:04:26.260
 Jail was grabbing at Makin's wrist and able to stop it moving remorselessly upwards.

04:04:26.260 --> 04:04:32.580
 They rolled to a halt, Makin squeezed, twisted, jailed, pinned arm cracked.

04:04:32.580 --> 04:04:38.580
 Jail screamed high and long as a stuck bore, the fight draining from him.

04:04:38.580 --> 04:04:44.740
 Then Makin's knife was at Jail's throat, tip pressing into the soft flesh at the base of the jaw.

04:04:44.740 --> 04:04:47.140
 "Please," Jail sobbed.

04:04:48.420 --> 04:04:50.900
 "For Castell," Makin whispered.

04:04:50.900 --> 04:04:54.500
 Then he shoved the blade up with all his strength.

04:04:54.500 --> 04:05:01.780
 Jail made a choking sound, gurgling on dark blood that welded from his mouth dribbled down his chin.

04:05:01.780 --> 04:05:08.660
 He struggled, but Makin pushed the blade deeper on into his skull, kept pushing until the knife's

04:05:08.660 --> 04:05:10.660
 hilt was tight to Jail's flesh.

04:05:10.660 --> 04:05:17.380
 Jail's eyes bulged, then he spasomed, legs kicking slowed, became still.

04:05:18.020 --> 04:05:22.500
 "Making wronged away," slowly stood and looked down upon Jail.

04:05:22.500 --> 04:05:30.660
 He grimaced, part snarled, felt suddenly weak and dropped to his knees, then sat and stared at Jail's corpse.

04:05:30.660 --> 04:05:33.780
 "You are avenged, Castell."

04:05:33.780 --> 04:05:36.580
 "You were like a son to me."

04:05:36.580 --> 04:05:41.940
 He felt his shoulders begin to shake, tears blur his vision,

04:05:41.940 --> 04:05:46.900
 and then a hand was striking his head, a warm body beside him pulling him into an embrace.

04:05:46.900 --> 04:05:54.660
 "He laid his head upon Fridale's breast and wept. He didn't know how long he remained like that,

04:05:54.660 --> 04:06:00.020
 but in time, the world opened up from that small pinpoint of grief, and he became aware of voices.

04:06:00.020 --> 04:06:05.380
 He looked up and saw the warband of Ripper gathered in a half-circle about him.

04:06:05.380 --> 04:06:11.380
 There it is, Krelis, Albin, Alcyon, and so many others, hundreds of them, all watching him.

04:06:12.980 --> 04:06:19.300
 "Well, that was a cracking fire and old and eyeing," Krelis said, nodding to my keen,

04:06:19.300 --> 04:06:23.460
 lifting a skin of mead to his lips and drinking deep. "What now?"

04:06:23.460 --> 04:06:29.140
 Fidale answered. "Now we march on Drasil."

04:06:29.140 --> 04:06:35.940
 CHAPTER 18

04:06:38.580 --> 04:06:43.380
 Coven stood in the great courtyard before the gates of Drasil, alongside her fellow prisoners.

04:06:43.380 --> 04:06:48.580
 Caledus walked down the staircase that led to the battlements where he had announced his

04:06:48.580 --> 04:06:54.660
 challenge to Corbin as he did each and every morning. "Save the lives of your people.

04:06:54.660 --> 04:06:56.500
 Stop their torture."

04:06:56.500 --> 04:07:03.860
 As always, Corven did not come, and now Caledus began the second half of each day's ritual,

04:07:03.860 --> 04:07:08.180
 choosing a prisoner to be impaled within the courtyard.

04:07:08.820 --> 04:07:14.260
 "Almost a moon had passed since Drasil had fallen so unimaginably quickly.

04:07:14.260 --> 04:07:17.460
 A moon of heartache and pain."

04:07:17.460 --> 04:07:23.940
 Although she was a prisoner, Coen had been allowed to take charge of the makeshift hospice

04:07:23.940 --> 04:07:28.660
 that she and Brenad spent so long stalking and preparing, choosing a few staff to help her

04:07:28.660 --> 04:07:33.540
 from amongst the more able-bodied prisoners. She was permitted to heal the captured,

04:07:33.540 --> 04:07:37.620
 only if she also looked after those of the fairs army who had been wounded in the battle.

04:07:38.260 --> 04:07:44.900
 "Much as Coen despised doing so, she knew it was the only way to help her own people."

04:07:44.900 --> 04:07:50.660
 Caledus stopped to dozen steps up from the courtyard and looked at the gathered prisoners.

04:07:50.660 --> 04:07:57.780
 "It seems that your bright star has better things to do than save your lives," he said.

04:07:57.780 --> 04:07:59.620
 "Voice laced with anger."

04:07:59.620 --> 04:08:03.940
 Coen shivered involuntarily at the thought of what was the calm of the screams.

04:08:05.620 --> 04:08:07.300
 "She was no stranger to death now.

04:08:07.300 --> 04:08:11.060
 But nothing could make her immune to the horror she witnessed each morning."

04:08:11.060 --> 04:08:12.980
 Coen.

04:08:12.980 --> 04:08:14.500
 "Come and save us."

04:08:14.500 --> 04:08:18.740
 With each passing day, it seemed more impossible.

04:08:18.740 --> 04:08:23.300
 For the first few days, she had been practically convinced that her brother would somehow

04:08:23.300 --> 04:08:26.820
 return with a war band and a win-back Drasil defeat their enemy.

04:08:26.820 --> 04:08:31.620
 But with each screen filled morning, that hope had withered.

04:08:33.300 --> 04:08:38.260
 Caledus gave a curtain nod, and a catish him stepped out from the shadows of the stable blocks,

04:08:38.260 --> 04:08:40.660
 moving amongst the prisoners, dragging one forwards.

04:08:40.660 --> 04:08:47.460
 As always, Coen's heart seemed to freeze, feeling as if it swelled to fill her chest

04:08:47.460 --> 04:08:50.260
 as a single catish him walked down the line that she was standing in.

04:08:50.260 --> 04:08:55.940
 "It was the figure that was always surrounded by billowing clouds of flies."

04:08:55.940 --> 04:08:58.580
 It paused before her.

04:08:59.620 --> 04:09:02.820
 One fist grabbing her chin and lifting it to stare into her eyes,

04:09:02.820 --> 04:09:06.020
 though there was nothing there, its eyes were black, soulless wells.

04:09:06.020 --> 04:09:12.180
 A lunatic grin twisted its mouth in a black tongue flicked out from its mouth,

04:09:12.180 --> 04:09:15.380
 thick and swollen, and slowly licked her cheek.

04:09:15.380 --> 04:09:20.820
 She reached from its foul breath, but the catish him held her immovable,

04:09:20.820 --> 04:09:23.700
 while flies crawled over her face up her nose.

04:09:25.620 --> 04:09:36.500
 "One day, soon!" it whispered in her ear, "I will crash your skull and suck the jelly from your eyes."

04:09:36.500 --> 04:09:43.460
 Then it released her, grabbing the man beside her, one of those who had been saved from the

04:09:43.460 --> 04:09:48.980
 Van Thalen all benches, and dragged him towards a stake. He began to plead, then wail.

04:09:50.500 --> 04:09:56.340
 It did not good. And soon his horrific screams were ringing out, a cacophony of torment.

04:09:56.340 --> 04:09:59.060
 There was no hiding from it.

04:09:59.060 --> 04:10:06.660
 The sound climbed, sweeping over the walls, and on, out over the plains surrounding the

04:10:06.660 --> 04:10:08.900
 fortress into the silent trees of form.

04:10:08.900 --> 04:10:13.700
 Have Corbin and the survivors fled? Or retreated?

04:10:15.300 --> 04:10:19.460
 Call it a strode down from the back of a step, and with an irritable wave of his hand,

04:10:19.460 --> 04:10:21.860
 signaled for the surviving prisoners to be taken away.

04:10:21.860 --> 04:10:27.540
 The warriors of Tenabral in black and silver, heard it co-in and the others out of the courtyard.

04:10:27.540 --> 04:10:32.740
 She wrinkled her nose as they passed the stables, the stench of Nefair's drag,

04:10:32.740 --> 04:10:38.180
 clawing up her nose. She had smelt a lot of bad things in her time, but nothing like

04:10:38.180 --> 04:10:43.620
 the smell of drag dung. She heard a horse nay as they moved past the stables.

04:10:44.260 --> 04:10:51.860
 SHIELD. When Drassel had fallen to Callidus and Nefair's warband, the stables had been full of

04:10:51.860 --> 04:10:57.140
 horses, great war horses at the Jihad Road, a whole herd that had been saved from the destruction

04:10:57.140 --> 04:11:03.780
 of Graham's hold. They were still there, and created another task that prisoners were used for,

04:11:03.780 --> 04:11:10.100
 stabled UT, tending to the horses. Every time that Corbin was picked, she had managed to get

04:11:10.100 --> 04:11:16.260
 close to SHIELD, Corbin's stallion. As they left the courtyard and entered a wide street,

04:11:16.260 --> 04:11:19.220
 shouts rang out from the wall, then a horn sounded.

04:11:19.220 --> 04:11:25.460
 The great bars across the gates were drawn back, and the gates opened with a juddering creek.

04:11:25.460 --> 04:11:31.060
 Figures filled the open gates, silhouettes with the sign behind them.

04:11:31.060 --> 04:11:34.820
 They became clearer as they spilt into the courtyard.

04:11:35.780 --> 04:11:39.700
 Vin Thalen, a score, two score, maybe more. Many of them were wounded.

04:11:39.700 --> 04:11:48.420
 So something is out there then. Hidden within the trees of form. Something with teeth of iron.

04:11:48.420 --> 04:11:54.660
 As she was marched away from the courtyard, Coen felt a seed of hope, glimmer, deep inside.

04:11:54.660 --> 04:12:00.820
 It was faints and fragile, and it wasn't helped much by what she saw around her on her way

04:12:00.820 --> 04:12:06.660
 back to the hospice. Caddishing were prowling the streets, moving like shadows, their heads,

04:12:06.660 --> 04:12:12.660
 twitching at every sound. All around her, she saw a host of Eagle Guard in her black and silver,

04:12:12.660 --> 04:12:17.460
 manning gates and walls, filling once abandoned buildings, working at forge and barn,

04:12:17.460 --> 04:12:22.260
 and the Vin Thalen were everywhere. Many of them were half drunk and fighting,

04:12:22.260 --> 04:12:26.660
 loitering on street corners, sitting in impromptu circles and throwing dice of bone.

04:12:28.340 --> 04:12:33.060
 The numbers of her enemies seemed vast, far more than Corbin's war band had ever been,

04:12:33.060 --> 04:12:40.580
 even a full strength. Could we ever have won? The dead from the battle had mostly been cleared

04:12:40.580 --> 04:12:45.700
 from the streets now, here and there a dark stain on a flagstone acting as a stark reminder.

04:12:45.700 --> 04:12:51.860
 As Coen turned a corner, she saw a dog sniffing in a heap to rubbish pile.

04:12:51.860 --> 04:12:57.780
 The dog was small and white, a ratter. I know that dog.

04:12:58.100 --> 04:13:05.700
 It was Halen's. What happened to him? She looked at the dog as she was marched past it,

04:13:05.700 --> 04:13:11.940
 it was skinny and half starved, ribs visible. Halen must be dead. He loved that dog,

04:13:11.940 --> 04:13:20.500
 pots, he called him. Just like my poor buddye. What happened to him? She had not seen him since

04:13:20.500 --> 04:13:26.820
 before the battle. Perhaps he'd been killed or maybe flared, though, deep in her heart she doubted

04:13:26.820 --> 04:13:30.900
 that. He was too loyal, would not have left me like that.

04:13:30.900 --> 04:13:35.300
 She drew level with the white dog and clicked her tongue,

04:13:35.300 --> 04:13:38.500
 reached inside a pocket in her cloak and pulled out a chunk of bread.

04:13:38.500 --> 04:13:45.620
 The dog lifted its head sniffing and after a moment's cautious indecision, darted over to her.

04:13:45.620 --> 04:13:50.660
 She dropped the piece of bread and caught it definitely, and it was gone.

04:13:52.260 --> 04:13:57.140
 She watched it scamper away, turn a corner and disappear. For a moment,

04:13:57.140 --> 04:13:59.940
 she thought she saw something waiting for it moving in the shadows.

04:13:59.940 --> 04:14:07.140
 Guards ushered her and the other prisoners into the hospice, less than 300 of them now because

04:14:07.140 --> 04:14:12.420
 of Caledas's morning ritual. The building was large enough to accommodate their numbers with

04:14:12.420 --> 04:14:18.660
 the lower floor made of two interlinking chambers. Part of it had been partitioned off for the

04:14:18.660 --> 04:14:22.020
 care of the injured. The rest turned into a makeshift prison for the others.

04:14:22.020 --> 04:14:26.980
 Only one guard came into the hospice, the rest sitting out in the courtyard.

04:14:26.980 --> 04:14:30.100
 Cohen heard the sound of dice on a throwboard.

04:14:30.100 --> 04:14:36.500
 Automatically, she went into the adjoining chamber and checked on the injured, not many of them

04:14:36.500 --> 04:14:42.260
 left now. There had been a lot more after the battle, but many had died. Cohen being unable

04:14:42.260 --> 04:14:45.460
 to do a little more for them than ease their passing across the bridge of swords.

04:14:47.140 --> 04:14:51.380
 Now only a score remained in here, although from what she'd just seen,

04:14:51.380 --> 04:14:55.060
 she expected that her skill would now be required for the injured of enthalin.

04:14:55.060 --> 04:14:58.900
 Frankly, she'd rather poison than heal them.

04:14:58.900 --> 04:15:05.620
 Do not give up, she told herself. Remembering her time as a prisoner with an affair in Caledas.

04:15:05.620 --> 04:15:12.820
 All had seemed hopeless then. That time, Corbin had come out of nowhere and rescued her.

04:15:14.100 --> 04:15:19.140
 Although ma'am died in the undertaking. I'll not let that happen again. People dying for my

04:15:19.140 --> 04:15:23.940
 saving. I'll not wait around to be rescued. I will make my own fortune. Whatever the cost.

04:15:23.940 --> 04:15:32.500
 Cohen opened her eyes. After counting 100 heartbeats and not hearing anything else but the usual

04:15:32.500 --> 04:15:39.300
 snoring, she turned her head to check on their enthalin guard. As expected, he was asleep.

04:15:40.900 --> 04:15:45.060
 Beyond the doors she heard the muted sound of conversation, the occasional burst of laughter,

04:15:45.060 --> 04:15:48.500
 the rest of their guards sitting in the courtyard drinking and gambling.

04:15:48.500 --> 04:15:55.300
 At first, their guards had been vigilant and rightly so because there had been a

04:15:55.300 --> 04:15:59.460
 smattering of Jihad amongst the captives and they did not take well to being made prisoners.

04:15:59.460 --> 04:16:04.260
 On the first night, two had attempted escape killing eight guards,

04:16:04.260 --> 04:16:06.580
 maiming three more and setting fire to another.

04:16:08.180 --> 04:16:12.740
 Eventually, they had both been subdued and executed in the courtyard the next day.

04:16:12.740 --> 04:16:18.820
 Since then, no more escapes had been attempted and over time the guards had become

04:16:18.820 --> 04:16:25.380
 correspondingly less vigilant. Cohen patted slowly from the room, making her way to a set of

04:16:25.380 --> 04:16:30.260
 stairs leading up to a balcony that looked down upon the main hall with a dozen rooms opening

04:16:30.260 --> 04:16:37.460
 off it. Almost silently, she passed into one of those rooms. There was one large window that

04:16:37.460 --> 04:16:41.300
 let in a wide beam of moonlight, shockingly bright in the darkness.

04:16:41.300 --> 04:16:47.860
 Cohen traced a familiar path to a cupboard, opened the door, shifted a loose board inside,

04:16:47.860 --> 04:16:54.100
 and lifted out a package. She shuffled over to the window, sat with her back to the wall,

04:16:54.100 --> 04:16:59.940
 facing the dark silhouette of the open doorway. She opened the old linen she'd wrapped round it

04:16:59.940 --> 04:17:05.780
 to reveal a book, leather bound and worn. She opened it towards the back and started

04:17:05.780 --> 04:17:15.700
 reading the spidery script, wood, eigen, low, hara, agada, a guarding spell.

04:17:15.700 --> 04:17:23.780
 Akachir Anteil, boiling water, worm root, flayed skin.

04:17:23.780 --> 04:17:32.420
 She paused there, a shiver goose bumping her flesh. What did I expect from a book of giant spells?

04:17:33.460 --> 04:17:38.820
 She pulled a face, fear, and revulsion. It depends either skin belonged to, I suppose,

04:17:38.820 --> 04:17:42.100
 if it came from Caledus or Nefair or Lycus, Moorcant or Rin,

04:17:42.100 --> 04:17:47.140
 the list grew in her mind of enemies she'd like to do terrible things to.

04:17:47.140 --> 04:17:55.140
 Bruno said, "It is a tool, not an evil of itself. It is how I use it. That's important."

04:17:55.140 --> 04:18:01.460
 She became aware of a sound, a soft snuffling from out of the window,

04:18:01.460 --> 04:18:09.220
 leaves rustled. Something in herbed beds. Slowly, as quietly as she could manage,

04:18:09.220 --> 04:18:11.860
 she peered up over the window's edge and looked out.

04:18:11.860 --> 04:18:17.860
 Something was moving through the herb garden, nose to the ground, moving steadily toward the

04:18:17.860 --> 04:18:23.860
 hospice. It paused, its white form reflecting moonlight, and looked up at Cohen.

04:18:25.380 --> 04:18:32.180
 It's the dog from earlier, Halen's ratter. The dog turned in a circle and jumped on the spot.

04:18:32.180 --> 04:18:39.780
 Cohen was scared they would start barking. Then, movement caught her eye, further back in a

04:18:39.780 --> 04:18:44.420
 shadowed recess on the far side of the herb garden, a solid patch in the darkness.

04:18:44.420 --> 04:18:50.660
 It wind, moved into the moonlight. Cohen's breath caught in her chest.

04:18:51.860 --> 04:18:58.740
 Good eye. Without thinking, she jumped from the window, dropping into the soft earth of her bed.

04:18:58.740 --> 04:19:03.540
 Before she had righted herself, Good Eye was bounding across the soft earth,

04:19:03.540 --> 04:19:06.580
 hurling himself against her rough tongue, licking her face, whining.

04:19:06.580 --> 04:19:12.660
 Shh. She whispered. Tears blurring her eyes as she kissed his muzzle.

04:19:12.660 --> 04:19:15.940
 He didn't listen to her sloppily licking her face.

04:19:17.300 --> 04:19:21.940
 Where have you been? She whispered, scratching him behind one floppy ear,

04:19:21.940 --> 04:19:24.340
 running her other hand along the thick muscle of his neck.

04:19:24.340 --> 04:19:27.620
 Been feeding alright by the look of you?

04:19:27.620 --> 04:19:33.940
 Something was tied around him. Cohen lifted it and inspected the long strip of leather.

04:19:33.940 --> 04:19:41.780
 A leash. Then another sound caught her attention, a rustling close by in her bed,

04:19:41.780 --> 04:19:46.020
 amongst the thick leaves of the basil and peppermint. She squinted,

04:19:46.740 --> 04:19:50.180
 narrowed her eyes, saw someone appear from between the greenery,

04:19:50.180 --> 04:19:56.180
 a face, small and pale, dirt stained. It was hailing.

04:19:56.180 --> 04:20:01.300
 Chapter 19.

04:20:01.300 --> 04:20:02.820
 Uphas.

